# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: royal-manchester-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/altrincham-hospital] The hospital was built to replace the aging Altrincham General Hospital in Market Street.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/altrincham-hospital] The new hospital, which was built by Pochins, a Cheshire-based construction company, opened in April 2015.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/altrincham-hospital] The new facilities installed at the commissioning of the new hospital included digital radiography equipment costing £350,000.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Anshen and Allen was founded by Samuel Robert "Bob" Anshen (1910-1964) and William Stephen "Steve" Allen Jr.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Anshen was born in Revere, Massachusetts, in 1910 to Louis Joseph Anshen and Sarah Jaffee, both of whom were Jewish immigrants from Eastern Europe.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] At the time of his birth, they owned a jewelry shop and were prosperous enough to afford a servant.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Allen was born in Neptune Township, New Jersey, in 1912.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Their relationship began while they were studying at the University of Pennsylvania School of Architecture.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Upon graduation, they both received a traveling fellowship that eventually led them to San Francisco in 1937.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Their first project was the Davies House, a 6,000-square-foot (560 m2) Tudor Gothic inspired mansion in Woodside, California, commissioned by Ralph K.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Davies, a senior vice-president of Standard Oil of California.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] The house was completed on November 30, 1941.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] After the end of World War II, as a generalist practice, the firm developed gas station prototypes for Standard Oil, parking garages and interior naval architecture.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Elmer Gavello, Joseph Eichler and John Calder Mackay, residential real estate developers, commissioned Anshen and Allen to build the initial Gavello homes, Eichler homes and Mackay Homes in the California Modernist style beginning in the 1950s.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] The firm continued to design tract housing and custom homes until 1962.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, under the leadership of Derek Parker, the firm was transformed into a modern international architectural practice.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] During the mid-2000s, Anshen and Allen adopted the use of Building Information Modeling (BIM).
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] In 2007, Anshen and Allen participated in the development of Integrated Project Delivery by serving on the IPD Definition Task Group of the American Institute of Architects (AIA) California Council.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Anshen and Allen used shipping containers in their design for clinics for Containers 2 Clinics (C2C), a nonprofit organization that provides access to healthcare for women and children in rural areas.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] In 2009 the firm was identified as specializing in sustainable designs for the healthcare and academic markets.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] Anshen and Allen was acquired by Stantec in 2010.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/anshen-allen] The Anshen and Allen papers are kept in the Environmental Design Archives at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The hamlet of Blackley was mentioned in the Domesday Book.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The name derives from the Anglo-Saxon Blæclēah, which means "dark wood" or "dark clearing".
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] In the 13th and 14th centuries, Blackley was referred to as *Blakeley* or *Blakelegh*.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] By the Middle Ages, Blackley had become a park belonging to the lords of Manchester.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Its value in 1282 was recorded as £6 13s 4d, a sum approximately equivalent in buying power to £333,500 today.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The lords of Manchester leased the land from time to time.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] In 1473, John Byron held the leases on Blackley village, Blackley field and Pillingworth fields at an annual rent of £33 6s 8d.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The Byron family continued to hold the land until the beginning of the 17th century, when Blackley was sold in parcels to a number of landowners.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] By the middle of the 17th century, Blackley was a rural village of just 107 inhabitants.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There was gradual residential development in the 1930s to 1960s, where most farmland was built upon.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Today, only pockets of the suburb are undeveloped green space, with farmland remaining close to the M60 motorway.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley has an important history in the chemical industry, starting with the Borelle Dyeworks founded by Angel Raphael Louis Delaunay in 1785 and run by ICI, who expanded it as a research centre for chemicals and pharmaceuticals.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There were several other dye and chemical works.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Connolly's Ltd made telecommunication cabling, later becoming part of BICC.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley, since 2024, has been part of the parliamentary constituency of Blackley and Middleton South.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The current Member of Parliament is Graham Stringer of the Labour Party, who was first elected in 1997 for the predecessor constituency Manchester Blackley.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The candidate of the Reform UK came second in the general election of 2024, with 21.1% of the vote compared to Stringer's 53.8%.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The suburb is split between the local government wards of Higher Blackley and Charlestown on Manchester City Council.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The three councillors for both wards are members of the Labour Party.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley was historically in the ancient parish of Manchester, in 1866 Blackley became a civil parish, on 26 March 1896 the parish was abolished to form North Manchester.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] In 1891 the parish had a population of 7332.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] During the 1930s, residential development started to take place in the formerly rural village to provide more homes for Manchester's growing population.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It became an area with a mixture of housing: mainly privately owned homes for owner occupation and private renting.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] In 2014, Blackley appeared on a list of *Top 10 Places to Live In Greater Manchester*.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The suburb is popular for commuters into Manchester city centre.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The few opportunities to work in the suburb itself include the Hexagon Tower Development, close to North Manchester Hospital, which is a centre for scientific research into plastics and related innovation.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The Church of St Peter on Old Market Street is a Gothic Revival church, which was built in 1844 by E.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It was designated a Grade II* listed building on 20 June 1988.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The interior is aisled and particularly impressive for its complete 170 year old interior, with the extremely unusual survival of all the fine boxes and pews.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The churchyard contains the war graves of ten service personnel of World War I, and seven of World War II.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Boggart Hole Clough is a large woodland and urban country park.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The park has a bowling green, tennis and basketball courts, a boating lake and a children's play area.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It has its own permanent orienteering course and an athletics track.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There is an old stone bridge across the brook running through the clough.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The clough was designated a local nature reserve in 2008.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley Forest is a Site of Biological Importance and an example of one of the country's first Community Woodlands.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It was planted to commemorate the Queen's coronation and also local people killed in the Second World War.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The area has had woodland on it since the Norman Conquest in 1066, when there were wild boar, deer and eagles.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The forest is a mix of woodland, grassland and wetlands, with a network of paths and steps.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The stretch of the River Irk in the forest is fringed by birch trees with some colonies of autumn crocus.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Heaton Park, at around 650 acres (2.63 km2), is the biggest park in Greater Manchester, and one of the largest municipal parks in Western Europe, providing some 25% of Manchester's total green space.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It is the grounds of Heaton Hall, a Grade I listed, neoclassical 18th-century country mansion.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The hall was remodelled to a design by James Wyatt in 1772, and is open to the public as a museum and events venue.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Although the park is officially part of the City of Manchester, two of a number of entrances are accessed from the suburb of Blackley, on Middleton Road.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley is well served by buses primarily along the main arterial routes of Rochdale Road (A664), and Cheetham Hill Road/Bury Old Road (A665) directly to and from Manchester city centre.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Initially these would have been provided by the precursors to, and Manchester Carriage and Tramways Company, and currently by First Greater Manchester.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Other journeys are provided by Stagecoach Manchester, which took over JPT in April 2014.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There are frequent Metrolink trams from Bowker Vale to and from Manchester city centre and as far south as Altrincham and as far north as Bury.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The M60 orbital motorway is the northern boundary of Blackley.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There are nearest secondary schools, including Manchester Communication Academy.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The award-winning Blackley Golf Club has occupied its present site close to the M60 motorway since 1937.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The club celebrated its centenary in 2007, and a new clubhouse opened in 2009.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The clubhouse offers use for wedding receptions and private hire.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] There is a golf shop, open to club members and the public.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] The course's green is separated by fields from the motorway.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] A public footpath runs along the perimeter.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] Blackley Cricket Club currently plays in the Greater Manchester Cricket League.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/blackley] It won the cricket league title for Greater Manchester in 2009.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] Booth Hall was built during the early 17th century by Humphrey Booth, a Salford man noted for his philanthropy.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] The original hall building was demolished in 1907, and the site was acquired by Prestwich Poor Law Union for the construction of a new general-purpose infirmary in 1908.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It cared for the poor and the wounded soldiers from the First World War.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It reverted to being a children's hospital in 1926.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It had 750 beds in 1929 and was the third largest children's hospital in the UK.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It incorporated a 102-bed convalescent home.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It had 160 tuberculosis beds at a home in North Wales.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] The infirmary was equipped to give sunlight treatment to orthopaedic cases.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] The hospital was emptied at the start of the Second World War and made ready for expected air-raid casualties.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] A renal dialysis unit was opened by Princess Michael of Kent in 1980.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] After services transferred to the Royal Manchester Children's Hospital, Booth Hall Children's Hospital closed on 12 June 2009.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It provided pediatric specialist services, general pediatric services and had a pediatric accident and emergency department, providing pediatric surgery, orthopedic surgery, plastic surgery and a pediatric burns unit, gastroenterology, respiratory medicine and diabetology.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/booth-hall-children-s-hospital] It had a high dependency unit and a transitional care unit for long term, usually ventilated, patients.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The company was established as **Lendlease** by Dick Dusseldorp in 1958 to provide finance for building contracts being undertaken by Civil & Civic.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 1961, the company acquired Civil & Civic from Bredero's Bouwbedrijf.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease first listed on the ASX in 1962.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Operations expanded to the United States in 1971 and to Singapore in 1973.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 1982, Lendlease acquired 50% of MLC and in 1985 acquired the balance of the company.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] MLC's multi-manager, multi-style investment philosophy was introduced in 1986.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] It was later sold to National Australia Bank in the year 2000 for $4.56 billion, one of the biggest mergers in Australian corporate history.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 1999, the company formed Actus Lendlease with the acquisition of Actus Corporation's MILCON and technical service construction management business, and augmented this business with professionals from Lendlease Design and Lendlease Development.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Around this time, the company also acquired the British-based builder Bovis Construction from P&O.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] During 2000, it bought Amresco's commercial mortgage business.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] One year later, Lendlease acquired Delfin (now Lendlease Communities) for $172 million.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] It went on to buy Crosby Homes (now Lendlease Residential Development) for circa £240 million in 2005.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2009, Steve McCann was appointed CEO.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In the same year Lendlease Corporation acquired Babcock and Brown Communities, rebranding the business as Lendlease Primelife.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] At the time, this acquisition made Lendlease Australia's largest provider of retirement villages.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In December 2009, Lendlease was selected by the New South Wales Government to develop Barangaroo.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2010, Lendlease announced their first foray into the consumer market with Lendlease Solar.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] This subsidiary was wound up in early 2011, with no explanation as to why the division had closed.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] On 17 February 2011 Lendlease announced wider ranging changes to its group of brands.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] This announcement meant the retirement of the Bovis, Delfin, Vivas, Catalyst and Primelife brands which were superseded by the unified Lendlease brand.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In late February 2011, Lendlease acquired DASCO in order to position itself to take advantage of the impending Obama administration Health sector boom.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The company was immediately rebranded as Lendlease DASCO, and started operating independently of the Lendlease Americas business.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In March 2011, Lendlease completed the acquisition of Valemus (previously known as Bilfinger Berger Australia) from Bilfinger.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In March 2013, the business divested its aged care homes (from the acquisition of Babcock and Brown Communities) to Allity, a business owned by Australian Aged Care Partners.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2015, the company rebranded to use "Lendlease" as a single word.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In December 2016, Lendlease formed a joint venture agreement with Energy Made Clean.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Energy Made Clean is a wholly owned subsidiary of renewable energy technology developer, Carnegie Clean Energy (ASX: CCE).
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] With EMC and Carnegie's joint offerings, it is the only company in the world to offer a combination of wave, solar, wind, storage and desalination via microgrids.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Microgrids are a budding industry and this partnership aims to provide end-to-end technologies that deliver energy independence and a reliable alternative to traditional forms of energy in regional, remote and fringe-of-grid locations in Australia, United States and around the world.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In February 2021, Lendlease announced that Tony Lombardo, previously CEO of Lendlease Asia, would takeover from Steve McCann as Group CEO.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The global COVID-19 pandemic led to enforced site closures during the early 2020s, impairing revenues.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In February 2022, Lendlease reported a first half loss of $264 million, which it attributed to one-off restructuring costs, COVID-19 issues and asset sales.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The company cut about 360 jobs and garnered savings of $160 million.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] An improved second half to the financial year saw the company post a bottom-line loss of $99 million for the full year, after $333 million in writedowns on existing operations, a 61% drop in development EBITDA to $18 million and a 24% slump in construction earnings to $131 million.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In May 2024, Lendlease announced plans to sell its overseas operations and to be focused on its domestic operations in Australia by late 2025.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] It described its overseas markets as a "drag" on shareholder returns; its new strategy will focus on simplifying the firm's structure, reducing costs and leveraging its competitive strengths.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] On 1 January 2025, Lendlease announced the sale of its UK construction business to US private equity business Atlas Holdings for £35 million, with completion targeted before the end of June 2025.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The deal was completed in March 2025 when the business was renamed Bovis, resurrecting a brand retired in 2011.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease's regeneration projects include Barangaroo South in Sydney, Docklands, Victoria in Melbourne, the RNA Showgrounds in Brisbane, and Adelaide Oval in Adelaide.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] One of Lendlease's more controversial communities projects is their development for housing and industry of the former Australian Defence Industries (ADI) land at St Marys (Ropes Crossing & Jordan Springs) in Western Sydney.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Some of the group's major communities projects include Springfield Lakes, Queensland.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Their ADI property is the largest intact area of the biodiverse and endangered plant community, the "Cumberland Plain Woodland".
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease Asia has been working on two large urban development projects: The Exchange TRX (previously known as TRX Lifestyle Quarter) in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, and Paya Lebar Quarter in Singapore.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease Project Management & Construction (previously Bovis Lendlease) provided construction management services for the National September 11 Memorial & Museum in New York, in addition to a number of other major public buildings throughout the U.S.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] A Public Private Partnership involved InterContinental Hotels Group and Lendlease, where they joined forces in the Privatization of Army Lodging to deliver quality hotels to United States Army Soldiers, their Families, and official guests of the United States Army.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] This partnership created IHG Army Hotels, a division of InterContinental Hotels Group.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Other urban regeneration projects include Southbank, an area of Chicago, Illinois.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Soaring Heights, a 6 MW solar development at Davis-Monthan AFB, Tucson, Arizona, United States, is a large Public Partnerships business in the US.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In Europe, major urban regeneration programmes are underway in Elephant and Castle as Elephant Park, and in Stratford, London, as The International Quarter London.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease also worked as project manager on a new township at Durrat Al Bahrain on Bahrain Island.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In Europe, Lendlease Project Management & Construction provide project management and construction services for new projects and programmes.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2015, Lendlease oversaw the restoration of the encaustic tile pavements at The Houses of Parliament.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2008, the company and a subcontractor abatement firm, the John Galt Corporation, were charged with numerous OSHA safety violations after a fire broke out and killed two firefighters at the Deutsche Bank Building, a Manhattan skyscraper being demolished in the wake of the September 11 attacks.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The violations included an employee (Safety Manager) of "Lendlease's Project Management & Construction Business" filling out a safety check list that identified a stand-pipe as being present and functional - when it was actually disconnected in a hard to see spot.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The firemen consulted the check list, thought they had a good system and proceeded up into the building to fight the fire.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Only when they reached the dangerous area that was on fire, did they realise the system did not have any water pressure, and they died trying to retreat amid the confusion.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] As of June 2011, two out of the three individuals charged in the associated manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide case have been acquitted.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In 2012, Lendlease agreed to pay $56 million in fines and restitution after admitting that the company had routinely over-billed clients and evaded government rules regarding the hiring of women and minority-owned firms.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] For a ten-year time span ending in 2009, the company along with others devised a scheme to defraud federal, state and local government contracting agencies as well as private clients.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] The fine is the largest in the city's history.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] On 29 October 2012 the long boom of a Lendlease construction crane atop the 1,004 foot high One57 snapped during Hurricane Sandy forcing the evacuation of several buildings in Midtown Manhattan.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In October 2018, Lendlease was announced as a contender for a £330 million contract to renovate Manchester Town Hall.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Manchester's Opposition Leader and former MP John Leech uncovered a history of legal, ethical and worker safety controversy surrounding the two shortlisted companies (Laing O'Rourke and Lendlease).
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] He said that "Under absolutely no circumstances" should Lendlease ever be considered for a council contract again until they paid a £3 million Grenfell-style cladding bill in the Green Quarter of Manchester.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] In January 2019, Lendlease was announced as the winner of the contract.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Leech criticised the decision and said it showed a lack of concern for local people.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] A 23-year-old worker was killed and two others seriously injured in October 2020 on a Lendlease construction site at Curtin University in Western Australia.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] This occurred when the roof on the new School of Design and the Built Environment building collapsed.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease has been criticised for the Figtree Hill development, near the Gilead area of south-west Sydney, due to its land clearing and development threatening the only healthy and growing Koala population in New South Wales.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Koalas were uplisted to endangered in 2022, facing population declines due to habitat loss caused by catastrophic bushfires, encroaching urban development and chlamydia.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease proposed nature corridors to allow Koala populations to cross between habitats either side of developments.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Environmental groups raised concern over the narrowness of corridors and how effective it would be.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/bovis-lend-lease] Lendlease sold the development to Stocklands midway through delivering the first Koala underpass to cross Alpin road, and refused to allow Stocklands access to the other side of the road to complete the underpass, leaving Koala populations stranded.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] The **Royal Manchester Children's Hospital** is a children's hospital in Oxford Road, Manchester, England.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] The Royal Manchester Children's Hospital is managed by the Manchester University NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was required to replace services previously provided by the Pendlebury Children's Hospital at Pendlebury in the City of Salford, Booth Hall Children's Hospital at Blackley in north-Manchester, and neonatal care from Saint Mary's Hospital, Manchester.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] It was procured under a Private Finance Initiative contract in 2004.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] The new hospital, which was designed by Anshen & Allen and built by Bovis Lend Lease at a cost of approximately £500 million, was completed in April 2009 and opened in June 2009.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] In 2013 the hospital carried out scans on Ta-Kr-Hb a mummified Egyptian woman dating from 7th or 8th century BC.
[src:royal-manchester-children-s-hospital/royal-manchester-children-s-hospital] The hospital has 371 beds and with 185,000 annual patient visits making it the largest and busiest children's hospital in the United Kingdom.
